'Aufonomy for Councils':
New North Campus advisor
In an effort to improve the North Campus society, dramatically
and normally, two new resident advisors have been added to the
men's hall structure. They join Terry Moore and Gene robert who
are beginning their second year as advisors.
Dave Johnson, advisor for North and South counter and Smith,
in addition will work as an assistant in the history department. Johnson is currently
studying for his PhD. in history
at the University of Minnesota
and has taken a year off for
reading.
Although it is still quite early
in the academic year, Johnson
already has some thoughts about
the resident advisor program
and Grinnell society. He felt
that the mobile behind the begin
central advisor system has not
been “clearly anticipated by the
administration” thus bringing
about a certain amount of district for the advisor among the
students. As far as disciplinary
action Johnson said the form
Councils should have complete
autonomy in this area but that
he might aid in the enforcement of quiet hours.
“I expected a closed society
at Griiinell, and I was not disappointed," Johnson continued.
“Upperclassmen have the notion
that Grinnell is the centersofa
the~universe and does not need
improvement." He cited the
fact that some of the classes
at Grinnell are as large as anniversary classes and emphasized
the selfrconsciousness of std»
cents towards their college as
unique.
Paul Thurston, advisor for
Clark and liable, is also a dealtime student this year. Because
Thurston worked last semester
on a sociology project at Costa
Rica, he had to return to com»
plate his graduation requirements. In addition he will assist
in coaching Freshmen football,
Along with eleven other students from colleges in the Mine
west Conference, Thurston
studied the problems of Costa
Tivo Grinnell students
with him were Nancy Moritz
on a sociology project and
Chuck cornell doing work in
biology. Thurston consolidated
on the poverty in the capital
San Jose, intervention seventyfive families and discussing
their problems and the urban
migration with them. Although
he was only there six months,
he thought that he had acquired
very valuable field experience.
