Friday September V. I?“
Dan Bucks
The gentle chaos of reducing m
Grinnell — expanding, following old
friends, learning new faces -— was in<
permitted in a thought-providing manner
by the opening corporation. The remarks of President suggest and Mr.
Wall offered a challenge to the students
and the rest of the college to question
constructively the institutions of {his
community and to contribute to die bet<
cement of the Grinnell experience.
in viewing the empty student chairs in
party that evening one could only wonder whether the students would accurately respond to this invitation to involvement. A critical appraisal of our
student culture would seem to workforce
die {ear that the remarks of Monday
evening are likely to receive little attention or concern. Grinnell students appear obtained ln a visual psychology
that excluded a sense of societal motion-
[ion and commitment. At the heart of
this psychology is the failure of the majority of students to engage in a concern,
liberal, intellectual endeavor. While
there is much energy extended in accu‘
relating facts and information (or assigned material, there ls little commitment to the idea of scholars enterprise
63111811 an in the context of I. community. A narrow self- orientation has
been constitutes {or a critical awareness
of ideas, values, and beliefs; and competition for grades too often replaced a
vigorous, cooperative interactive of
viewpoints. Perhaps most gardening is
the lack of a quality of contemporaneity;
for Grinnell students, in contrast to the
same generation elsewhere, display a re.
guidance to reverse themselves in the
moral and social issues of our time.
The symptoms of the lethargy of the
student community can be distinguished
more easily than can its sources. However, the caused factors device, perhaps,
from the dominant influence on students
of the culture outside of Grinnell, from
the nature of our educational system,
and from the inadequacies of student
leadership, broader defined.
The intellectual luggage that smdenis
bring to Grinnell often contains strong
element of competitive individualism,
materialism, and status consequences.
These Values military against the idci
ol 3 community dedicated to learning
for learning's sake and proceeding intellectually as a cooperative enterprise.
Our e cultural structure promo:es a
restriction sell-Concern by lodging intel-
lecture achievement through one com.
police score — the grade point average.
A cost is review when intellectual cure
parties lead students too far shield of the
present domain of credits and grades.
Moreover, Gtinncll education proceeds
in a discovered sequence. Knowledge is
imported early, but the techniques and
attitudes necessary to (he self-acquisition of knowledge are anticipated late
in the college career. Thus, the ability of
Giinnell’s “apprenticescholars” to teach
themselves and each other —« an ability
essential to a similarly community —- is
inadequately developed.
Finally, campus organizations and
governments — potentially effective links
between the students and the college —
are often maintaining, tradition-bound.
and hureaucretically overweight. Their
internal motivation force is more currently a desire for peer group approval
and rec nylon than a sense of societal
respond y for the state of the community. OpErating according to partition’s law, the organizations percentage
themselves in narrow, integrate, and he
efficient fashion.
Unfortunately. these causes of the
psychology of non—community are proc
able subject to influence — if they can
be inﬂdenied at all — only in the long
run. Such institutions and patterns 0! liehavlor change slowly and with difficulty
if attacked from within.
A more immediate impact would den
live from the compensation forces of a
reception from outside of the present patterns. A reception not in the form of protest, but in the form of the establishment
of independent intellectual enterprises.
Research, study, and discussion organized without regard to their present contents would provide both a motivation
outlet for frustrated authorities and a
non-restriction atmosphere in which contemporary moral and social dilemmas
could be controlled. Most importantly,
such student activity would constitute a
positive intellectual Contribution to the
community — a contribution that would
be achieved in a cooperative similarly
fashion and that pulled force Students to
teach themselves and each other.
Hopellllly, this college need not produce only well-trained philips but also
individuals who think and act in terms
or values and purposes. With a bit of inspiration and independent action, cells
year can be more than a full science
of dendlillcs and examinations.
 
